{{Infobox film | name = A Change of Sex | image = | alt = | caption = | director = David Pearson | producers = Roger Mills {{nowrap|{{small|(executive producer)}}}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba18f3edd |title=Roger Mills |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[BFI Film & TV Database]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |access-date=2016-03-30}}</ref> | starring = Julia Grant | narrator = <!-- or: | narrators = --> | music = | cinematography = [[Mike Southon (cinematographer)|Mike Southon]] | editing = {{unbulleted list|[[David Gladwell]]|Tony Heaven}} | studio = <!-- or: | production companies = --> | distributor = [[BBC2]] | released = {{film date|1979|06|25|United Kingdom|df=yes}} | runtime = | country = England | language = English | budget = | gross = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. "£11.6 million" not "£11,586,221")--> }}
'''''A Change of Sex''''' is a multi-part [[television documentary]] about English [[trans woman]] Julia Grant. The first chapter, initially titled ''George'', premiered on [[BBC2]] in 1979. It is one of the first [[documentary film]]s about [[transgender]] issues.
BBC2 repeated the programme in 1980, followed by two new chapters, ''Julia: The First Year'' and ''Julia: My Body, My Choice''. A revised version aired in 1994, accompanied by another new chapter, ''The Untold Story'', which updates viewers on Julia's life of the past 15 years. The final instalment, ''Julia Gets Her Man'', followed in 1999. David Pearson directed the films.
Julia Grant was born in 1954.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Grant |first=Julia |subject-link= |interviewer=Sam Johnson |title=Julia Grant - The Transgender Zone Interviews |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7GG6AiDAcKk |type=Interview: video |website=[[YouTube]] |date=25 March 2014 |access-date=2016-03-30}}</ref> The documentary introduces us to her as George Roberts, a catering manager. Although she performs as a [[drag queen]], George says she has never felt at home in [[gay male culture]]. She feels inside that she is a woman, and she wishes for [[Sex reassignment surgery (male-to-female)|sex reassignment surgery]]. The [[National Health Service]] refers her to the Gender Identity Clinic at [[Charing Cross Hospital]]. As she sits in the consulting room, we hear the voice of her psychiatrist, but we never see his face. His attitude toward Julia is stern and disparaging.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/television-review-a-change-isnt-always-as-good-as-a-rest-1377341.html |title=Television (Review) / A change isn't always as good as a rest |last=Sutcliffe |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster) |date=18 August 1994 |website=[[The Independent]] |access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> His deskside manner was the inspiration for the character [[List of The League of Gentlemen characters#Additional characters|Dr Ira Carlton]], a "despotic GP who rules his patients with eccentric zeal" in the [[black comedy]] series ''[[The League of Gentlemen]]''.<ref>{{cite book |title=The League of Gentlemen |last=Hunt |first=Leon |year=2008 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |page=124 |isbn=978-1-84457-269-4 |oclc=226357069}}</ref>
Beyond the consulting room, the filmmakers follow Julia through her experiences of [[Hormone replacement therapy (transgender)|hormone therapy]], shopping for women's clothing, [[Gender confirmation surgery|gender confirmation surgeries]],<ref name="letter">{{cite web |url=http://gscene.com/news/letter-to-editor-manchester-pride/ |title=Letter to Editor: Manchester Pride |date=17 October 2013 |last1=Ledward |first1=James |last2=Grant |first2=Julia |website=Gscene |access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> her professional life, and other dimensions of her [[Transitioning (transgender)|transition]].
==Production and broadcast== ''A Change of Sex'' began as an episode of ''Inside Story'', a documentary [[television series]] oriented toward [[investigative journalism]]. There was sufficient interest in the episode—which was titled ''George''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b72d95407 |title=George (1979) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[BFI Film & TV Database]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |access-date=2016-03-30}}</ref>—for Pearson to explore Julia's story further. He and his crew filmed her progress in 1979 and 1980. ''George'' was retitled ''George: The Big Decision'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6feabcf8 |title=George - The Big Decision (1980) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[BFI Film & TV Database]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> and the more recent footage was edited into two new chapters: ''Julia: The First Year''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6feabff2 |title=Julia - The First Year (1980) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[BFI Film & TV Database]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> and ''Julia: My Body, My Choice''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6feac2cb |title=Julia - My Body, My Choice (1980) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[BFI Film & TV Database]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> This three-film series was titled ''A Change of Sex'', and BBC2 broadcast it in October 1980. [[New English Library]] published Julia's autobiography, ''George and Julia'', that same month.<ref>{{cite book |last=Grant |first=Julia |title=George and Julia |date=1980 |publisher=[[New English Library]] |location=London |isbn=0-450-04715-6 |oclc=64747941}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://theheroines2.blogspot.com/2014/04/julia-grant-george-and-julia.html |title=Julia Grant - ''George and Julia'' |date=28 April 2014 |website=Transgender Biography Books |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925000032/https://theheroines2.blogspot.com/2014/04/julia-grant-just-julia-story-of.html |archive-date=2016-09-25 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>
In 1993, Pearson revisited Julia to film a fourth chapter of the documentary about her life.<ref name="justjulia">{{cite book |title=Just Julia: The Story of an Extraordinary Woman |last=Grant |first=Julia |date=1994 |publisher=Boxtree |isbn=978-1-85283-481-4 |oclc=31755479}}</ref>{{rp|269}} Filming and editing continued into 1994,<ref name="justjulia"/>{{rp|269}} but the earlier programmes were also edited in order to make a four-part story into a trilogy: ''George & Julia'', ''Desperate Measures'', and ''The Untold Story''. This revised version of ''A Change of Sex'' aired on BBC2 in August 1994. The broadcast coincided with the publication of Julia's second memoir, ''Just Julia: The Story of an Extraordinary Woman''.<ref name="justjulia"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://theheroines2.blogspot.com/2014/04/julia-grant-just-julia-story-of.html |title=Julia Grant - ''Just Julia: The Story of an Extraordinary Woman'' |date=27 April 2014 |website=Transgender Biography Books |access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref>
In 1998, Pearson filmed Julia once more. BBC2 repeated the 1994 edition of the previous films in July and August 1999 before broadcasting the final chapter, ''Julia Gets Her Man''.<ref name="bfi-gets">{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b841a6525 |title=Julia Gets Her Man (1999) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[BFI Film & TV Database]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> It updates viewers on developments in Julia's life over the past four years—including a new job and a growing relationship.<ref name="bfi-gets"/>
