'''Denny Martin Flinn''' (December 21, 1947- August 24, 2007) was an American [[Choreography|choreographer]], [[writer]], and [[Stage Director|stage director]] and actor with numerous [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits. He co-wrote the screenplay for ''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]'' (1991).

==Biography==
Flinn grew up in [[California]], spending his early life in the cities of [[Los Angeles]] and [[San Francisco]]. He attended the [[San Francisco State University]],<ref name="Cox">{{cite news|last1=Cox|first1=Gordon|title=Denny Martin Flinn, 59, actor, writer, choreographer, director|url=https://variety.com/2007/legit/markets-festivals/denny-martin-flinn-59-actor-writer-choreographer-director-1117971999/|accessdate=14 December 2017|work=Variety|date=September 14, 2007}}</ref> his [[academic major]] being theatre. While still in college, Flinn performed as a dancer in [[North Beach, San Francisco]].<ref name="Broadway World">{{cite web|title=Broadway Actor & Author, Denny Martin Flinn, Dies at 59|work=Broadway World.com|date=September 7, 2007|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/Broadway-Actor-Author-Denny-Martin-Flinn-Dies-at-59-20070907|accessdate=June 19, 2013}}</ref> He later moved to [[New York City]], where he found employment as an actor, dancer, and choreographer. His [[Broadway theatre]] credits include the original musical ''[[Sugar (musical)|Sugar]]'' (1972), and revivals of ''[[Hello, Dolly! (musical)|Hello, Dolly!]]'' (1975) and ''[[Pal Joey (musical)|Pal Joey]]'' (1976).<ref name="Broadway World"/> His [[Off-Broadway]] credits include the choreography of ''Six'' (1971) by [[Charles Strouse]].<ref name="Broadway World"/> He also performed in the national tour of ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]''. In the 80s Flinn toured with the national company of ''[[A Chorus Line]]'' in the roles of both Zack and Greg.<ref name="Cox"/><ref name="Broadway World"/>

Flinn later wrote and directed his own Off-Broadway musical: ''Groucho'' (1979),<ref name="Cox"/> starring [[Lewis J. Stadlen]].<ref name="Broadway World"/> He choreographed musical sequences for the films ''[[The Deceivers (film)|The Deceivers]]'' (1988) and ''[[Ghost (1990 film)|Ghost]]'' (1990),<ref name="Cox"/> and the television series ''[[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]'' and ''[[Search for Tomorrow]]''.

Flinn wrote the 1989 book ''What They Did for Love: The Untold Story Behind the Making of A Chorus Line'', covering the story behind the production of the 1970s musical ''A Chorus Line''. He next turned to [[mystery fiction]], writing the novels ''San Francisco Kills'' (1990) and ''Killer Finish'' (1991). He and [[Nicholas Meyer]] co-wrote the script of ''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]'' (1991).<ref name="Broadway World"/><ref name="Cox"/> Flinn also wrote [http://en.memory-alpha.org/wiki/The_Fearful_Summons The Fearful Summons] (1995), a [[List of Star Trek novels|Star Trek novel]].<ref name="Broadway World"/> His research work ''Musical! A Grand Tour - the Rise, Glory and Fall of an American Institution'' (1997) won an [[Deems Taylor|ASCAP Deems Taylor Award]]. His later output consisted of non-fiction books such as ''How Not To Write a Screenplay: 101 Common Mistakes Most Screenwriters Make'' (1999) and ''How Not To Audition: Avoiding the Common Mistakes Most Actors Make'' (2003).<ref name="Broadway World"/>

Flinn died in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]] due to "complications from cancer". He was survived by a wife and two children.<ref name="Broadway World"/>

