{{italic title}} {{Other uses|Fougere (disambiguation){{!}}Fougere}}
[[File:Fougère Royale by Paul Parquet - Bottle.jpg|thumb|200px|right|An original bottle of ''Fougère Royale'' by [[Houbigant Parfum|Houbigant]], created by the perfumer [[Paul Parquet]] in 1882.<ref name=Houbigant/>]] [[File:sa-fern.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Fougère means "[[fern]]" in [[French language|French]] ]]
'''''Fougère''''', {{IPA-fr|fu.ʒɛʁ|pron}}, is one of the main [[Perfume#Olfactive families|olfactive families]] of [[perfume]]s. The name comes from the [[French language]] word for "[[fern]]". ''Fougère'' perfumes are made with a blend of fragrances: [[Note (perfumery)|top-notes]] are sweet, with the scent of [[lavender]] flowers; as the more [[Volatility (chemistry)|volatile]] components evaporate, the scents of [[oakmoss]], derived from a species of [[lichen]] and described as woody, sharp and slightly sweet, and [[coumarin]], similar to the scent of new-mown [[hay]], become noticeable. Aromatic ''fougère'', a derivative of this class, contains additional notes of herbs, spice and/or wood.<ref name=Fragrantica>{{cite web|title=Aromatic Fougere|url=http://www.fragrantica.com/groups/aromatic+fougere.html|website=Fragrantica.com perfumes magazine|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>
The name originated with [[Houbigant Parfum]]'s ''Fougère Royale''. This perfume, created by Houbigant owner [[Paul Parquet]], was later added to the scent archives known as the [[Osmothèque]], in [[Versailles, France]].<ref name=Houbigant>{{cite web|title=Fougère Royale|url=https://www.houbigant-parfum.com/us_en/fougere-royale.html|website=Parfums Houbigant Paris|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> Houbigant re-introduced this fragrance in 2010.<ref name=Fragrantica/>
Perfumes of this type are especially popular as fragrances for men.<ref name=Houbigant/> Many modern fougère perfumes have various citrus, herbaceous, green, floral and animalic notes included. The most common additions to the basic fragrance blend include [[vetiver]] and [[pelargonium|geranium]]. [[Bergamot orange|Bergamot]] is often present to add sharpness to the lavender top-note.
Examples of men's fragrances which fall into the ''fougère'' class include [[Brut (cologne)|Brut]] by [[Fabergé (cosmetics)|Fabergé]], [[Paco Rabanne]] Pour Homme, Azzaro Pour Homme, Boss by [[Hugo Boss (fashion designer)|Hugo Boss]], [[Prada]] for Men, [[Eternity (fragrance)|Eternity for Men]] by [[Calvin Klein]], Canoe for Men by Dana, [[Dolce & Gabbana]] Pour Homme, [[Drakkar Noir]] by [[Guy Laroche]], [[Tabac (perfume)|Tabac]] for Men, Michael for Men by [[Michael Kors]], Clubman Pinaud After Shave and Special Reserve, Polo Blue and Chaps by [[Ralph Lauren]], and [[Kouros (perfume)|Kouros]] by [[Yves Saint Laurent (brand)|Yves Saint Laurent]].<ref name=Houbigant/><ref name=Fragrantica/>
